"type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the very numerous places called Clifton, from Old English <i>clif</i> ‘slope’ (see   Cliff  ) + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’."],"variants":[{"name":"Cliff","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called Cliff(e), Cle(e)ve, or Clive, from Old English <i>clif</i> ‘slope, bank, cliff’, or a topographic name from the same word. The Old English word was used not only in the sense of modern English <i>cliff</i> but also of much gentler slopes and frequently also of a riverbank or seashore."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":7,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":52,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Nicholas de Clifton was born in 1330, in Stonyhurst, Lancashire, England, his father, Sir William Clifton, was 26 and his mother, Margaret Sherburne, was 22. He married Eleanor West about 1352, in Snitterfield, Warwickshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1382, in London, England, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1330–1382":"1330–1382","1334–Female":"1334–Surnud","1353–1382":"1353–1382","1355–1395":"1355–1395","1305–1365":"1305–1365","1309–1365":"1309–1365","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1334":"1334","1355":"1355","1365":"1365","1453":"1453","1353":"1353","21 September 1348":"21. september 1348","about 1352":"umbes 1352","1309":"1309","after 1365":"pärast 1365","Snitterfield, Warwickshire, England":"Snitterfield, Warwickshire, England","Christ Church Greyfriars Newgate, London, England":"London, England","Salwick, Lancashire, England":"Salwick, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stonyhurst, Lancashire, England":"Stonyhurst, Lancashire, England","Salwick, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Salwick, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shrewsbury, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1330–1382":"1330–1382","1334–Female":"1334–Kuollut","1353–1382":"1353–1382","1355–1395":"1355–1395","1305–1365":"1305–1365","1309–1365":"1309–1365","13